.Dd June 5, 2026
.Dt EPUBSCRUB 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm epubscrub
.Nd sanitize EPUB files by removing common exploit vectors
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl -dryrun
.Op Fl -fix
.Op Fl -policy Ar calm Ns | Ns Ar wary Ns | Ns Ar paranoid
.Op Fl -calm | Fl -wary | Fl -paranoid
.Op Fl -report Ar file
.Op Fl -report-format Ar text Ns | Ns Ar json
.Ar input.epub
.Op Fl o Ar output.epub
.Nm
.Fl -help
.Nm
.Fl -version
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
opens an EPUB archive, inspects each ZIP entry, removes or rewrites risky
content, and optionally writes a cleaned EPUB.
.Pp
It is a sanitizer, not a guarantee that a file is malware-free.
It is intended
to reduce common EPUB attack surfaces such as active markup, embedded scripts,
unsafe archive entries, and unexpected binary payloads.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl -dryrun
Run the full scan and in-memory sanitization pass without writing an output
EPUB.
The report shows whether the file is clean, would be sanitized, or is
rejected.
Removed files include a short reason.
Modified content includes the first affected line number and a short reason.
The legacy
.Fl -check
spelling is accepted as a compatibility alias.
.It Fl -fix
Allow safe structural EPUB repairs while writing an output EPUB.
Currently this repairs
.Pa mimetype
placement and compression by writing it as the first ZIP entry, stored
uncompressed.
.It Fl -report Ar file
Write the report to
.Ar file
instead of standard output.
When used without
.Fl o ,
.Nm
runs as a report-only dry run.
.It Fl -report-format Ar text Ns | Ns Ar json
Choose the report format.
The default is
.Ar text .
.It Fl -policy Ar calm Ns | Ns Ar wary Ns | Ns Ar paranoid
Choose the sanitization policy.
The default is
.Ar wary .
.It Fl -calm
Use the calm policy.
This removes clear active/script/executable payloads while leaving more normal
EPUB resources alone.
.It Fl -wary
Use the wary policy.
This is the default practical baseline.
.It Fl -paranoid
Use the paranoid policy.
This minimizes attack surface by also removing SVG, fonts, media, and external
text links.
.It Fl o Ar output.epub
Write the sanitized EPUB to
.Ar output.epub .
The output is written even when no changes are required.
The output path must not refer to the same file as the input.
Required unless
.Fl -dryrun
or report-only mode
is used.
.It Fl h , Fl -help
Show command usage.
.It Fl V , Fl -version
Show the program version.
.El
.Sh SANITIZATION POLICY
The default
.Ar wary
policy removes or rejects:
.Bl -bullet
.It
EPUB archives over the configured size limit.
.It
ZIP entries with path traversal, unsafe names, symlink behavior, unsupported
compression methods, extreme compression ratios, or invalid CRCs.
.It
JavaScript files, executable-like files, script files, nested archives, and
unknown file types outside the EPUB allowlist.
.It
.Li <script> ,
.Li <iframe> ,
.Li <object> ,
.Li <embed> ,
and form-control markup in XHTML, HTML, XML, NCX, and SVG content.
.It
Event handler attributes such as
.Li onclick
and
.Li onload .
.It
External links and resource loads in
.Li <a> ,
.Li <img> ,
.Li <link> ,
and
.Li <iframe>
tags.
.It
The javascript:, vbscript:, and unsafe data: schemes.
.It
CSS
.Li @import
rules and remote, script, or data URLs in CSS
.Li url(...)
values.
.El
.Pp
The default
.Ar wary
policy preserves local CSS, sanitized SVG files, internal navigation links,
standard EPUB metadata, images, and font files such as
.Pa .ttf ,
.Pa .otf ,
.Pa .woff ,
and
.Pa .woff2 .
.Pp
The
.Ar calm
policy is less disruptive and permits remote resource references except for
script-oriented URLs.
The
.Ar paranoid
policy is more aggressive and also removes SVG, fonts, and media.
.Pp
When a file is removed, matching OPF manifest entries are removed as well.
.Sh OUTPUT
Text reports include the input, optional output, status, policy, summary counts,
and event lines.
Sanitized file-content events include the first affected source line.
JSON reports include the same fields as structured data:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
epubscrub --dryrun --policy paranoid --report-format json book.epub
.Ed
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It 0
The input was already clean.
.It 1
The input was sanitized or would be sanitized when using
.Fl -dryrun .
.It 2
The input was rejected as unsafe or malformed.
.It 3
A read, write, parse, or command-line usage error occurred.
.It 4
An internal error occurred.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
Install the command and manual page:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
make install
.Ed
.Pp
Sanitize an EPUB:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
epubscrub book.epub -o book.clean.epub
.Ed
.Pp
Check an EPUB without writing a cleaned copy:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
epubscrub --dryrun book.epub
.Ed
.Pp
Write a report to a file:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
epubscrub book.epub -o book.clean.epub --report report.txt
.Ed
.Sh SECURITY NOTES
.Nm
cannot verify that the EPUB reader app itself is maintained.
Open files from
unknown sources with a current reader from a trusted vendor.
.Pp
Nested archives are not recursively unpacked.
They are removed because they are
outside the normal EPUB reading surface and can hide payloads.
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Nm
uses the ZIP container format used by EPUB files.
